

 1Ô∏è‚É£ WebDriver (Main Interface)

 ‚úÖ What is WebDriver?

WebDriver is the main Selenium interface used to control browser.

It acts like a remote control for browser.

üëâ WebDriver talks to:

* ChromeDriver ‚Üí Chrome
* GeckoDriver ‚Üí Firefox

---

 ‚úÖ Syntax

```java
WebDriver driver;
```

---

 ‚úÖ Example

```java
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();   // Launch browser
        driver.get("https://google.com");        // Open URL
        driver.quit();                           // Close browser
    }
}
```

---

 üîπ Important WebDriver Methods

| Method                      | Purpose              |
| --------------------------- | -------------------- |
| driver.get(url)             | Open website         |
| driver.getTitle()           | Get page title       |
| driver.getCurrentUrl()      | Get URL              |
| driver.close()              | Close current tab    |
| driver.quit()               | Close entire browser |
| driver.navigate().back()    | Go back              |
| driver.navigate().forward() | Go forward           |
| driver.navigate().refresh() | Refresh page         |

---

 2Ô∏è‚É£ ChromeDriver

 ‚úÖ What is ChromeDriver?

ChromeDriver is a class that controls Google Chrome browser.

It implements WebDriver interface.

---

 ‚úÖ Syntax

```java
WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
```

---

 ‚úÖ With Options

```java
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeOptions;

ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();
options.addArguments("--start-maximized");

WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(options);
```

---

 3Ô∏è‚É£ FirefoxDriver

FirefoxDriver uses GeckoDriver internally.

---

 ‚úÖ Syntax

```java
WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver();
```

---

 ‚úÖ Example

```java
import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver;

WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver();
driver.get("https://example.com");
```

---

 4Ô∏è‚É£ WebElement

 ‚úÖ What is WebElement?

WebElement represents HTML element on webpage.

Example:

* Button
* Textbox
* Link
* Checkbox

---

 ‚úÖ Syntax

```java
WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("username"));
```

---

 ‚úÖ Common WebElement Methods

| Method         | Purpose             |
| -------------- | ------------------- |
| sendKeys()     | Type text           |
| click()        | Click               |
| getText()      | Get text            |
| getAttribute() | Get attribute value |
| isDisplayed()  | Check visibility    |
| isEnabled()    | Check enabled       |
| isSelected()   | Check selected      |

---

 ‚úÖ Example

```java
WebElement user = driver.findElement(By.id("username"));
user.sendKeys("Uday");

WebElement loginBtn = driver.findElement(By.id("login"));
loginBtn.click();
```

---

 5Ô∏è‚É£ Locators in Selenium

Locators are used to identify elements.

---

 ‚úÖ Types of Locators

| Locator         | Syntax                    |
| --------------- | ------------------------- |
| id              | By.id("value")            |
| name            | By.name("value")          |
| className       | By.className("value")     |
| tagName         | By.tagName("input")       |
| linkText        | By.linkText("Login")      |
| partialLinkText | By.partialLinkText("Log") |
| cssSelector     | By.cssSelector("css")     |
| xpath           | By.xpath("xpath")         |

---

 ‚úÖ Example

```java
driver.findElement(By.id("email"));
driver.findElement(By.name("password"));
driver.findElement(By.className("form-control"));
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@type='text']"));
```

---

 6Ô∏è‚É£ XPath

XPath is most powerful locator.

---

 üîπ 6.1 Absolute XPath

Starts from root `/html`

Example:

```xpath
/html/body/div[1]/form/input[1]
```

---

 ‚ùå Disadvantages

* Very long
* Breaks easily
* Not recommended

---

 üîπ 6.2 Relative XPath ‚úÖ (Recommended)

Starts with `//`

Example:

```xpath
//input[@id='username']
```

---

 Syntax

```xpath
//tagname[@attribute='value']
```

---

 Example in Selenium

```java
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@id='username']")).sendKeys("Uday");
```

---

 üîπ 6.3 Relative XPath with Tag Name

```xpath
//button[@type='submit']
```

```java
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[@type='submit']")).click();
```

---

 üîπ 6.4 text() in XPath

Used when element text is visible.

---

 Syntax

```xpath
//tagname[text()='Exact Text']
```

---

 Example

```xpath
//button[text()='Login']
```

```java
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[text()='Login']")).click();
```

---

 üîπ 6.5 contains() in XPath

Used for partial matching.

---

 ‚úÖ Contains with attribute

```xpath
//input[contains(@id,'user')]
```

---

 ‚úÖ Contains with text

```xpath
//button[contains(text(),'Log')]
```

---

 Selenium Example

```java
driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[contains(text(),'Log')]")).click();
```

---

 7Ô∏è‚É£ Waits in Selenium

Waits are used for synchronization.

---

 üîπ 7.1 Implicit Wait

Waits globally for all elements.

---

 Syntax

```java
driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
```

---

 Example

```java
driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
driver.findElement(By.id("login")).click();
```

---

 üîπ 7.2 Explicit Wait

Waits for specific condition.

---

 Syntax

```java
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("login")));
```

---

 Example

```java
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));

WebElement ele = wait.until(
        ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.id("login")));

ele.click();
```

---

 üîπ 7.3 Fluent Wait

Advanced explicit wait with polling.

---

 Syntax

```java
Wait<WebDriver> wait = new FluentWait<>(driver)
        .withTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
        .pollingEvery(Duration.ofSeconds(2))
        .ignoring(NoSuchElementException.class);
```

---

 Example

```java
Wait<WebDriver> wait = new FluentWait<>(driver)
        .withTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
        .pollingEvery(Duration.ofSeconds(2))
        .ignoring(NoSuchElementException.class);

WebElement ele = wait.until(d -> 
        d.findElement(By.id("login")));

ele.click();
```

